The Butane Tank Injection is a batch-type process passed on seasonal RVP adjustments. Butane is received by truck (transports) and piped directly to and injected into the gasoline recirculation line. The butane is pumped by the tanker for direct injection into gasoline lines feeding the product storage tank(s). Process safety controls include a skid emergency shutoff valve with multiple, manual actuators and fusible element along with a Smart-Hose, low emission hose coupler, and thermal/hydrostatic reliefs. Access to the Champaign LP Terminal is restricted to authorized employees, management personnel and authorized contractors/visitors.

B. GENERAL ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM AND CHEMICAL-SPECIFIC PREVENTION MEASURES

The Champaign LP Terminal accidental release prevention and emergency planning/response programs help MPLX effectively manage the hazards posed by the regulated substance to the Terminal employees, surrounding public, and environment. The covered process is regulated by the EPA RMP regulation 40 CFR Part 68, as well as the OSHA Process Safety Management standard 29 CFR 1910.119 and the Illinois EPA. The following accident prevention program elements are in place at the Champaign LP Terminal:

1) Employee Participation;
2) Process Safety Information;
3) Process Hazard Analysis (PHA);
4) Standard Operating Procedures;
5) Training;
6) Contractors;
7) Pre-startup Safety Review;
8) Mechanical Integrity with Preventive Maintenance;
9) Hazardous Work Permits
